[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] In mathematics, an **initial algebra** is an initial object in the category of F-algebras for a given endofunctor F.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] This initiality provides a general framework for induction and recursion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] *F* : **Set** → **Set** sending X to 1 + *X*, where 1 is a one-point (singleton) set, a terminal object in the category.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] An algebra for this endofunctor is a set X (called the *carrier* of the algebra) together with a function *f* : (1 + *X*) → *X*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Defining such a function amounts to defining a point *x* ∈ *X* and a function *X* → *X*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Then the set **N** of natural numbers together with the function [zero,succ]: 1 + **N** → **N** is an initial F-algebra.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] The set of natural numbers is the carrier of an initial algebra for this functor: the point is zero and the function is the successor function.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] For a second example, consider the endofunctor 1 + **N** × (−) on the category of sets, where **N** is the set of natural numbers.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] An algebra for this endofunctor is a set X together with a function 1 + **N** × *X* → *X*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] To define such a function, we need a point *x* ∈ *X* and a function **N** × *X* → *X*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] The set of finite lists of natural numbers is an initial algebra for this functor.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] The point is the empty list, and the function is cons, taking a number and a finite list, and returning a new finite list with the number at the head.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] In categories with binary coproducts, the definitions just given are equivalent to the usual definitions of a natural number object and a list object, respectively.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Dually, a **final coalgebra** is a terminal object in the category of F-coalgebras.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] The finality provides a general framework for coinduction and corecursion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] For example, using the same functor 1 + (−) as before, a coalgebra is defined as a set X together with a function *f* : *X* → (1 + *X*).
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Defining such a function amounts to defining a partial function *f'*: *X* ⇸ *X* whose domain is formed by those $x\in X$ for which *f*(*x*) does not belong to 1.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Having such a structure, we can define a chain of sets: *X*0 being a subset of *X* on which *f*′ is not defined, *X*1 which elements map into *X*0 by *f*′, *X*2 which elements map into *X*1 by *f*′, etc., and *X**ω* containing the remaining elements of X.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] This set $\mathbf {N} \cup \{\omega \}$ that is the carrier of the final coalgebra of 1 + (−) is known as the set of conatural numbers.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] For a second example, consider the same functor 1 + **N** × (−) as before.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] In this case the carrier of the final coalgebra consists of all lists of natural numbers, finite as well as infinite.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] The operations are a test function testing whether a list is empty, and a deconstruction function defined on non-empty lists returning a pair consisting of the head and the tail of the input list.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Various finite data structures used in programming, such as lists and trees, can be obtained as initial algebras of specific endofunctors.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] While there may be several initial algebras for a given endofunctor, they are unique up to isomorphism, which informally means that the "observable" properties of a data structure can be adequately captured by defining it as an initial algebra.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] which makes this an F-algebra for the endofunctor F sending X to 1 + (*A* × *X*).
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] It is, in fact, *the* initial F-algebra.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Initiality is established by the function known as *foldr* in functional programming languages such as Haskell and ML.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Types obtained this way are known as algebraic data types.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] Types defined by using least fixed point construct with functor F can be regarded as an initial F-algebra, provided that parametricity holds for the type.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] In a dual way, similar relationship exists between notions of greatest fixed point and terminal F-coalgebra, with applications to coinductive types.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] These can be used for allowing potentially infinite objects while maintaining strong normalization property.
[src:structural-induction-pl/initial-algebra] In the strongly normalizing (each program terminates) Charity programming language, coinductive data types can be used for achieving surprising results, e.g. defining lookup constructs to implement such “strong” functions like the Ackermann function.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] — *Concrete Mathematics*, page 3 margins.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] A **proof by induction** consists of two cases.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The first, the **base case**, proves the statement for $n=0$ without assuming any knowledge of other cases.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The second case, the **induction step**, proves that *if* the statement holds for any given case $n=k$ , *then* it must also hold for the next case $n=k+1$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] These two steps establish that the statement holds for every natural number n .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The base case does not necessarily begin with $n=0$ , but often with $n=1$ , and possibly with any fixed natural number $n=N$ , establishing the truth of the statement for all natural numbers $n\geq N$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The method can be extended to prove statements about more general well-founded structures, such as trees; this generalization, known as structural induction, is used in mathematical logic and computer science.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Mathematical induction in this extended sense is closely related to recursion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Mathematical induction is an inference rule used in formal proofs, and is the foundation of most correctness proofs for computer programs.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Despite its name, mathematical induction differs fundamentally from inductive reasoning as used in philosophy, in which the examination of many cases results in a probable conclusion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The mathematical method examines infinitely many cases to prove a general statement, but it does so by a finite chain of deductive reasoning involving the variable n , which can take infinitely many values.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The result is a rigorous proof of the statement, not an assertion of its probability.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Joyce, there is no evidence for the use of the principle of mathematical induction in Euclid’s writings.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Acerbi (2000) argues that Plato’s *Parmenides* (c.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] 370 BC) contains traces of an early implicit inductive proof.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This interpretation has been challenged by Negrepontis and Farmaki (2021), who further state that neither Plato nor any of the other Pythagoreans used the principle of mathematical induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The earliest implicit proof by mathematical induction was written by al-Karaji around 1000 AD, who applied it to arithmetic sequences to prove the binomial theorem and properties of Pascal's triangle.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Whilst the original work was lost, it was later referenced by Al-Samawal al-Maghribi in his treatise *al-Bahir fi'l-jabr (The Brilliant in Algebra)* in around 1150 AD.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In India, early implicit proofs by mathematical induction appear in Bhaskara's "cyclic method".
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] None of these ancient mathematicians, however, explicitly stated the induction hypothesis.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Another similar case (contrary to what Vacca has written, as Freudenthal carefully showed) was that of Francesco Maurolico in his *Arithmeticorum libri duo* (1575), who used the technique to prove that the sum of the first n odd integers is *n*2.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The earliest rigorous use of induction was by Gersonides (1288–1344).
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The first explicit formulation of the principle of induction was given by Pascal in his *Traité du triangle arithmétique* (1665).
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Another Frenchman, Fermat, made ample use of a related principle: indirect proof by infinite descent.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The induction hypothesis was also employed by the Swiss Jakob Bernoulli, and from then on it became well known.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The modern formal treatment of the principle came only in the 19th century, with George Boole, Augustus De Morgan, Charles Sanders Peirce, Giuseppe Peano, and Richard Dedekind.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The simplest and most common form of mathematical induction infers that a statement involving a natural number n (that is, an integer *n* ≥ 0 or 1) holds for all values of n.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The **induction step** (or **inductive step**, or **step case**): prove that for every n, if the statement holds for n, then it holds for *n* + 1.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In other words, assume that the statement holds for some arbitrary natural number n, and prove that the statement holds for *n* + 1.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The hypothesis in the induction step, that the statement holds for a particular n, is called the **induction hypothesis** or **inductive hypothesis**.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] To prove the induction step, one assumes the induction hypothesis for n and then uses this assumption to prove that the statement holds for *n* + 1.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Authors who prefer to define natural numbers to begin at 0 use that value in the base case; those who define natural numbers to begin at 1 use that value.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Equating the extreme left hand and right hand sides, we deduce that: $0+1+2+\cdots +k+(k+1)={\frac {(k+1)((k+1)+1)}{2}}.$ That is, the statement $P(k+1)$ also holds true, establishing the induction step.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Induction is often used to prove inequalities.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] As an example, we prove that $\left|\sin nx\right|\leq n\left|\sin x\right|$ for any real number x and natural number n .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] At first glance, it may appear that a more general version, $\left|\sin nx\right|\leq n\left|\sin x\right|$ for any *real* numbers $n,x$ , could be proven without induction; but the case ${\textstyle n={\frac {1}{2}},\,x=\pi }$ shows it may be false for non-integer values of n .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This suggests we examine the statement specifically for *natural* values of n , and induction is the readiest tool.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The inequality between the extreme left-hand and right-hand quantities shows that $P(k+1)$ is true, which completes the induction step.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In practice, proofs by induction are often structured differently, depending on the exact nature of the property to be proven.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] All variants of induction are special cases of transfinite induction; see below.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Showing that if the statement holds for an arbitrary number *n* ≥ *b*, then the same statement also holds for *n* + 1.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This can be used, for example, to show that 2*n* ≥ *n* + 5 for *n* ≥ 3.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In this way, one can prove that some statement *P*(*n*) holds for all *n* ≥ 1, or even for all *n* ≥ −5.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This form of mathematical induction is actually a special case of the previous form, because if the statement to be proved is *P*(*n*) then proving it with these two rules is equivalent with proving *P*(*n* + *b*) for all natural numbers n with an induction base case 0.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Assume an infinite supply of 4- and 5-dollar coins.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Induction can be used to prove that any whole amount of dollars greater than or equal to 12 can be formed by a combination of such coins.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Let *S*(*k*) denote the statement "k dollars can be formed by a combination of 4- and 5-dollar coins".
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Therefore, by the principle of induction, *S*(*k*) holds for all *k* ≥ 12, and the proof is complete.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In this example, although *S*(*k*) also holds for ${\textstyle k\in \{4,5,8,9,10\}}$ , the above proof cannot be modified to replace the minimum amount of 12 dollar to any lower value m.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] For *m* = 11, the base case is actually false; for *m* = 10, the second case in the induction step (replacing three 5- by four 4-dollar coins) will not work; let alone for even lower m.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] It is sometimes desirable to prove a statement involving two natural numbers, n and m, by iterating the induction process.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] That is, one proves a base case and an induction step for n, and in each of those proves a base case and an induction step for m.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] See, for example, the proof of commutativity accompanying *addition of natural numbers*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] More complicated arguments involving three or more counters are also possible.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The method of infinite descent is a variation of mathematical induction which was used by Pierre de Fermat.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] It is used to show that some statement *Q*(*n*) is false for all natural numbers n.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Its traditional form consists of showing that if *Q*(*n*) is true for some natural number n, it also holds for some strictly smaller natural number m.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Because there are no infinite decreasing sequences of natural numbers, this situation would be impossible, thereby showing (by contradiction) that *Q*(*n*) cannot be true for any n.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The validity of this method can be verified from the usual principle of mathematical induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Using mathematical induction on the statement *P*(*n*) defined as "*Q*(*m*) is false for all natural numbers m less than or equal to n", it follows that *P*(*n*) holds for all n, which means that *Q*(*n*) is false for every natural number n.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] whereupon the induction principle "automates" n applications of this step in getting from *P*(0) to *P*(*n*).
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This could be called "predecessor induction" because each step proves something about a number from something about that number's predecessor.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The induction principle then "automates" log2 *n* applications of this inference in getting from *P*(0) to *P*(*n*).
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In fact, it is called "prefix induction" because each step proves something about a number from something about the "prefix" of that number — as formed by truncating the low bit of its binary representation.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] It can also be viewed as an application of traditional induction on the length of that binary representation.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] If traditional predecessor induction is interpreted computationally as an n-step loop, then prefix induction would correspond to a log-n-step loop.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Because of that, proofs using prefix induction are "more feasibly constructive" than proofs using predecessor induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Predecessor induction can trivially simulate prefix induction on the same statement.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] One can take the idea a step further: one must prove $\forall k\,\left(P\!\left(\left\lfloor {\sqrt {k}}\right\rfloor \right)\to P(k)\right)$ whereupon the induction principle "automates" log log *n* applications of this inference in getting from *P*(0) to *P*(*n*).
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This form of induction has been used, analogously, to study log-time parallel computation.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The name "strong induction" does not mean that this method can prove more than "weak induction", but merely refers to the stronger hypothesis used in the induction step.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In fact, it can be shown that the two methods are actually equivalent, as explained below.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In this form of complete induction, one still has to prove the base case, $P(0)$ , and it may even be necessary to prove extra-base cases such as $P(1)$ before the general argument applies, as in the example below of the Fibonacci number $F_{n}$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Although the form just described requires one to prove the base case, this is unnecessary if one can prove $P(m)$ (assuming $P(n)$ for all lower n ) for all $m\geq 0$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This is a special case of transfinite induction as described below, although it is no longer equivalent to ordinary induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In this form the base case is subsumed by the case $m=0$ , where $P(0)$ is proved with no other $P(n)$ assumed; this case may need to be handled separately, but sometimes the same argument applies for $m=0$ and $m>0$ , making the proof simpler and more elegant.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In this method, however, it is vital to ensure that the proof of $P(m)$ does not implicitly assume that $m>0$ , e.g. by saying "choose an arbitrary $n<m$ ", or by assuming that a set of m elements has an element.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Complete induction is equivalent to ordinary mathematical induction as described above, in the sense that a proof by one method can be transformed into a proof by the other.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Suppose there is a proof of $P(n)$ by complete induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Then, this proof can be transformed into an ordinary induction proof by assuming a stronger inductive hypothesis.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Let $Q(n)$ be the statement " $P(m)$ holds for all m such that $0\leq m\leq n$ "—this becomes the inductive hypothesis for ordinary induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] We can then show $Q(0)$ and $Q(n+1)$ for $n\in \mathbb {N}$ assuming only $Q(n)$ and show that $Q(n)$ implies $P(n)$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Complete induction is most useful when several instances of the inductive hypothesis are required for each induction step.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] By using the fact that $F_{n+2}=F_{n+1}+F_{n}$ for each $n\in \mathbb {N}$ , the identity above can be verified by direct calculation for ${\textstyle F_{n+2}}$ if one assumes that it already holds for both ${\textstyle F_{n+1}}$ and ${\textstyle F_{n}}$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] To complete the proof, the identity must be verified in the two base cases: $n=0$ and ${\textstyle n=1}$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Another proof by complete induction uses the hypothesis that the statement holds for *all* smaller n more thoroughly.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Consider the statement that "every natural number greater than 1 is a product of (one or more) prime numbers", which is the "existence" part of the fundamental theorem of arithmetic.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] For proving the induction step, the induction hypothesis is that for a given $m>1$ the statement holds for all smaller $n>1$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] If m is prime then it is certainly a product of primes, and if not, then by definition it is a product: $m=n_{1}n_{2}$ , where neither of the factors is equal to 1; hence neither is equal to m , and so both are greater than 1 and smaller than m .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The induction hypothesis now applies to $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ , so each one is a product of primes.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Thus m is a product of products of primes, and hence by extension a product of primes itself.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] We shall look to prove the same example as above, this time with *strong induction*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] However, there will be slight differences in the structure and the assumptions of the proof, starting with the extended base case.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Choosing $m=j-4$ , and observing that $15<j\implies 12\leq j-4<j$ shows that $S(j-4)$ holds, by the inductive hypothesis.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] That is, the sum $j-4$ can be formed by some combination of 4 and 5 dollar coins.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Then, simply adding a 4 dollar coin to that combination yields the sum j .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Sometimes, it is more convenient to deduce backwards, proving the statement for $n-1$ , given its validity for n .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] However, proving the validity of the statement for no single number suffices to establish the base case; instead, one needs to prove the statement for an infinite subset of the natural numbers.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] For example, Augustin Louis Cauchy first used forward (regular) induction to prove the inequality of arithmetic and geometric means for all powers of 2, and then used backwards induction to show it for all natural numbers.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The induction step must be proved for all values of n.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The base case $n=1$ is trivial, and the induction step is correct in all cases $n>1$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] However, the argument used in the induction step is incorrect for $n+1=2$ , because the statement that "the two sets overlap" is false for ${\textstyle \left\{1\right\}}$ and ${\textstyle \left\{2\right\}}$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] In words, the base case *P*(0) and the induction step (namely, that the induction hypothesis *P*(*k*) implies *P*(*k* + 1)) together imply that *P*(*n*) for any natural number n.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The axiom of induction asserts the validity of inferring that *P*(*n*) holds for any natural number n from the base case and the induction step.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The first quantifier in the axiom ranges over *predicates* rather than over individual numbers.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This is a second-order quantifier, which means that this axiom is stated in second-order logic.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Axiomatizing arithmetic induction in first-order logic requires an axiom schema containing a separate axiom for each possible predicate.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The article Peano axioms contains further discussion of this issue.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The successor function s of every natural number yields a natural number (*s*(*x*) = *x* + 1).
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This is not an axiom, but a theorem, given that natural numbers are defined in the language of ZFC set theory by axioms, analogous to Peano's.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] See construction of the natural numbers using the axiom of infinity and axiom schema of specification.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] One variation of the principle of complete induction can be generalized for statements about elements of any well-founded set, that is, a set with an irreflexive relation < that contains no infinite descending chains.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Every set representing an ordinal number is well-founded, the set of natural numbers is one of them.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Applied to a well-founded set, transfinite induction can be formulated as a single step.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] This form of induction, when applied to a set of ordinal numbers (which form a well-ordered and hence well-founded class), is called *transfinite induction*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] It is an important proof technique in set theory, topology and other fields.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] 3. when n has no direct predecessor, i.e. n is a so-called limit ordinal.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Strictly speaking, it is not necessary in transfinite induction to prove a base case, because it is a vacuous special case of the proposition that if *P* is true of all *n* < *m*, then *P* is true of m.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] It is vacuously true precisely because there are no values of *n* < *m* that could serve as counterexamples.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] So the special cases are special cases of the general case.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The principle of mathematical induction is usually stated as an axiom of the natural numbers; see Peano axioms.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] It is strictly stronger than the well-ordering principle in the context of the other Peano axioms.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] It can then be proved that induction, given the above-listed axioms, implies the well-ordering principle.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] The following proof uses complete induction and the first and fourth axioms.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] On the other hand, the set $\{(0,n):n\in \mathbb {N} \}\cup \{(1,n):n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ , shown in the picture, is well-ordered by the lexicographic order.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Moreover, except for the induction axiom, it satisfies all Peano axioms, where Peano's constant 0 is interpreted as the pair (0, 0), and Peano's *successor* function is defined on pairs by succ(*x*, *n*) = (*x*, *n* + 1) for all $x\in \{0,1\}$ and $n\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Then the base case *P*(0, 0) is trivially true, and so is the induction step: if *P*(*x*, *n*), then *P*(succ(*x*, *n*)).
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] However, *P* is not true for all pairs in the set, since *P*(1,0) is false.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Peano's axioms with the induction principle uniquely model the natural numbers.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] Replacing the induction principle with the well-ordering principle allows for more exotic models that fulfill all the axioms.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] It is mistakenly printed in several books and sources that the well-ordering principle is equivalent to the induction axiom.
[src:structural-induction-pl/mathematical-induction] A common mistake in many erroneous proofs is to assume that *n* − 1 is a unique and well-defined natural number, a property which is not implied by the other Peano axioms.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] In computer programming, a **recursive data type** is a data type whose definition contains values of the same type.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] It is also known as a **recursively defined**, **inductively defined** or **inductive data type**.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Data of recursive types are usually viewed as directed graphs.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] An important application of recursion in computer science is in defining dynamic data structures such as Lists and Trees.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Recursive data structures can dynamically grow to an arbitrarily large size in response to runtime requirements; in contrast, a static array's size requirements must be set at compile time.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Sometimes the term "inductive data type" is used for algebraic data types which are not necessarily recursive.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] This indicates that a list of a's is either an empty list or a **cons cell** containing an 'a' (the "head" of the list) and another list (the "tail").
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] This indicates that non-empty list of type `E` contains a data member of type `E`, and a reference to another List object for the rest of the list (or a null reference to indicate that this is the end of the list).
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Data types can also be defined by mutual recursion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] The most important basic example of this is a tree, which can be defined mutually recursively in terms of a forest (a list of trees).
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] A forest *f* consists of a list of trees, while a tree *t* consists of a pair of a value *v* and a forest *f* (its children).
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] This definition is elegant and easy to work with abstractly (such as when proving theorems about properties of trees), as it expresses a tree in simple terms: a list of one type, and a pair of two types.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] A tree *t* consists of a pair of a value *v* and a list of trees (its children).
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] This definition is more compact, but somewhat messier: a tree consists of a pair of one type and a list another, which require disentangling to prove results about.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] In type theory, a recursive type has the general form *μα*.*T* where the type variable *α* may appear in the type *T* and stands for the entire type itself.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] In type theory, we would say: ${\text{nat}}=\mu \alpha .1+\alpha$ where the two arms of the sum type represent the Zero and Succ data constructors.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Zero takes no arguments (thus represented by the unit type) and Succ takes another Nat (thus another element of $\mu \alpha .1+\alpha$ ).
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] There are two forms of recursive types: the so-called isorecursive types, and equirecursive types.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] The two forms differ in how terms of a recursive type are introduced and eliminated.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] To be precise: $roll:T[\mu \alpha .T/\alpha ]\to \mu \alpha .T$ and $unroll:\mu \alpha .T\to T[\mu \alpha .T/\alpha ]$ , and these two are inverse functions.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Under equirecursive rules, a recursive type $\mu \alpha .T$ and its unrolling $T[\mu \alpha .T/\alpha ]$ are *equal* – that is, those two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] In fact, most theories of equirecursive types go further and essentially specify that any two type expressions with the same "infinite expansion" are equivalent.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] As a result of these rules, equirecursive types contribute significantly more complexity to a type system than isorecursive types do.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Algorithmic problems such as type checking and type inference are more difficult for equirecursive types as well.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Since direct comparison does not make sense on an equirecursive type, they can be converted into a canonical form in O(n log n) time, which can easily be compared.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] Isorecursive types capture the form of self-referential (or mutually referential) type definitions seen in nominal object-oriented programming languages, and also arise in type-theoretic semantics of objects and classes.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] In functional programming languages, isorecursive types (in the guise of datatypes) are common too.
[src:structural-induction-pl/recursive-data-type] In TypeScript, recursion is allowed in type aliases.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Structural induction is used to prove that some proposition *P*(*x*) holds for all x of some sort of recursively defined structure, such as formulas, lists, or trees.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] A well-founded partial order is defined on the structures ("subformula" for formulas, "sublist" for lists, and "subtree" for trees).
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] The structural induction proof is a proof that the proposition holds for all the minimal structures and that if it holds for the immediate substructures of a certain structure S, then it must hold for S also.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] A structurally recursive function uses the same idea to define a recursive function: "base cases" handle each minimal structure and a rule for recursion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Structural recursion is usually proved correct by structural induction; in particularly easy cases, the inductive step is often left out.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] The *length* and ++ functions in the example below are structurally recursive.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] For example, if the structures are lists, one usually introduces the partial order "<", in which *L* < *M* whenever list L is the tail of list M.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Under this ordering, the empty list [] is the unique minimal element.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] A structural induction proof of some proposition *P*(*L*) then consists of two parts: A proof that *P*([]) is true and a proof that if *P*(*L*) is true for some list L, and if L is the tail of list M, then *P*(*M*) must also be true.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Eventually, there may exist more than one base case and/or more than one inductive case, depending on how the function or structure was constructed.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] 2. a proof that if *P*(*I*) is true for some instance I, and M can be obtained from I by applying any one recursive rule once, then *P*(*M*) must also be true.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] An ancestor tree is a commonly known data structure, showing the parents, grandparents, etc. of a person as far as known (see picture for an example).
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Hence, by structural induction, each ancestor tree satisfies the property.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Here ++ denotes the list concatenation operation, len() the list length, and L and M are lists.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] In order to prove this, we need definitions for length and for the concatenation operation.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Let (*h*:*t*) denote a list whose head (first element) is h and whose tail (list of remaining elements) is t, and let [] denote the empty list.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Our proposition *P*(*l*) is that EQ is true for all lists M when L is l.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] We want to show that *P*(*l*) is true for all lists l.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] We will prove this by structural induction on lists.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] First we will prove that *P*([]) is true; that is, EQ is true for all lists M when L happens to be the empty list [].
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] So this part of the theorem is proved; EQ is true for all M, when L is [], because the left-hand side and the right-hand side are equal.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Since I is nonempty, it has a head item, x, and a tail list, xs, so we can express it as (*x*:*xs*).
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] We would like to show that if this is the case, then EQ is also true for all values of M when *L* = *I* = (*x*:*xs*).
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Thus, from structural induction, we obtain that *P*(*L*) is true for all lists L.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Just as standard mathematical induction is equivalent to the well-ordering principle, structural induction is also equivalent to a well-ordering principle.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] If the set of all structures of a certain kind admits a well-founded partial order, then every nonempty subset must have a minimal element.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] (This is the definition of "well-founded".) The significance of the lemma in this context is that it allows us to deduce that if there are any counterexamples to the theorem we want to prove, then there must be a minimal counterexample.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] If we can show the existence of the minimal counterexample implies an even smaller counterexample, we have a contradiction (since the minimal counterexample isn't minimal) and so the set of counterexamples must be empty.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] As an example of this type of argument, consider the set of all binary trees.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] We will show that the number of leaves in a full binary tree is one more than the number of interior nodes.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Suppose there is a counterexample; then there must exist one with the minimal possible number of interior nodes.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] This counterexample, C, has n interior nodes and l leaves, where *n* + 1 ≠ *l*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Moreover, C must be nontrivial, because the trivial tree has *n* = 0 and *l* = 1 and is therefore not a counterexample.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] C therefore has at least one leaf whose parent node is an interior node.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] Delete this leaf and its parent from the tree, promoting the leaf's sibling node to the position formerly occupied by its parent.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] This reduces both n and l by 1, so the new tree also has *n* + 1 ≠ *l* and is therefore a smaller counterexample.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] But by hypothesis, C was already the smallest counterexample; therefore, the supposition that there were any counterexamples to begin with must have been false.
[src:structural-induction-pl/structural-induction] The partial ordering implied by 'smaller' here is the one that says that *S* < *T* whenever S has fewer nodes than T.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] In universal algebra and mathematical logic, a **term algebra** is a freely generated algebraic structure over a given signature.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] For example, in a signature consisting of a single binary operation, the term algebra over a set *X* of variables is exactly the free magma generated by *X*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] Other synonyms for the notion include **absolutely free algebra** and **anarchic algebra**.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] From a category theory perspective, a term algebra is the initial object for the category of all *X*-generated algebras of the same signature, and this object, unique up to isomorphism, is called an initial algebra; it generates by homomorphic projection all algebras in the category.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] A similar notion is that of a *Herbrand universe* in logic, usually used under this name in logic programming, which is (absolutely freely) defined starting from the set of constants and function symbols in a set of clauses.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] That is, the Herbrand universe consists of all ground terms: terms that have no variables in them.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] An atomic formula or *atom* is commonly defined as a predicate applied to a tuple of terms; a ground atom is then a predicate in which only ground terms appear.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] The *Herbrand base* is the set of all ground atoms that can be formed from predicate symbols in the original set of clauses and terms in its Herbrand universe.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] These two concepts are named after Jacques Herbrand.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] Term algebras also play a role in the semantics of abstract data types, where an abstract data type declaration provides the signature of a multi-sorted algebraic structure and the term algebra is a concrete model of the abstract declaration.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] A **type** $\tau$ is a set of function symbols, with each having an associated arity (i.e. number of inputs).
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] For any non-negative integer n , let $\tau _{n}$ denote the function symbols in $\tau$ of arity n .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] A constant is a function symbol of arity 0.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] Let $\tau$ be a type, and let X be a non-empty set of symbols, representing the variable symbols.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] (For simplicity, assume X and $\tau$ are disjoint.) Then the **set of terms** $T(X)$ of type $\tau$ over X is the set of all well-formed strings that can be constructed using the variable symbols of X and the constants and operations of $\tau$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] The **term algebra** ${\mathcal {T}}(X)$ of type $\tau$ over X is, in summary, the algebra of type $\tau$ that maps each expression to its string representation.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] The best-known algebra of type $\tau$ has the natural numbers as its domain and interprets 0 , 1 , + , and * in the usual way; we refer to it as ${\mathcal {A}}_{nat}$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] For the example variable set $X=\{x,y\}$ , we are going to investigate the term algebra ${\mathcal {T}}(X)$ of type $\tau$ over X .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] First, the set $T(X)$ of terms of type $\tau$ over X is considered.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] We use red color to flag its members, which otherwise may be hard to recognize due to their uncommon syntactic form.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] More generally, each string in $T(X)$ corresponds to a mathematical expression built from the admitted symbols and written in Polish prefix notation; for example, the term ${\color {red}*+x1x}$ corresponds to the expression $(x+1)*x$ in usual infix notation.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] No parentheses are needed to avoid ambiguities in Polish notation; e.g. the infix expression $x+(1*x)$ corresponds to the term ${\color {red}+x*1x}$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] To give some counter-examples, we have e.g.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] Now that the term set $T(X)$ is established, we consider the term algebra ${\mathcal {T}}(X)$ of type $\tau$ over X .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] This algebra uses $T(X)$ as its domain, on which addition and multiplication need to be defined.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] The addition function $+^{{\mathcal {T}}(X)}$ takes two terms p and q and returns the term ${\color {red}+}pq$ ; similarly, the multiplication function $*^{{\mathcal {T}}(X)}$ maps given terms p and q to the term ${\color {red}*}pq$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] Informally, the operations $+^{{\mathcal {T}}(X)}$ and $*^{{\mathcal {T}}(X)}$ are both "sluggards" in that they just record what computation should be done, rather than doing it.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] As an example for unique extendability of a homomorphism consider $g:X\to {\mathcal {A}}_{nat}$ defined by $g(x)=7$ and $g(y)=3$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] Informally, g defines an assignment of values to variable symbols, and once this is done, every term from $T(X)$ can be evaluated in a unique way in ${\mathcal {A}}_{nat}$ .
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] The **signature** *σ* of a language is a triple <*O*, *F*, *P*> consisting of the alphabet of constants *O*, function symbols *F*, and predicates *P*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] The **Herbrand base** of a signature *σ* consists of all ground atoms of *σ*: formulas of the form *R*(*t*1, ..., *t**n*), where *t*1, ..., *t**n* are terms containing no variables (i.e. elements of the Herbrand universe) and *R* is an *n*-ary relation symbol (*i.e.* predicate).
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] In the case of logic with equality, it also contains all equations of the form *t*1 = *t*2, where *t*1 and *t*2 contain no variables.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] The first-order theory of any term algebra can be shown to be decidable using quantifier elimination.
[src:structural-induction-pl/term-algebra] The complexity of the decision problem is in NONELEMENTARY because binary constructors are injective and thus pairing functions.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] More formally, a relation is well-founded if: $(\forall S\subseteq X)\;[S\neq \varnothing \implies (\exists m\in S)(\forall s\in S)\lnot (s\mathrel {R} m)].$ Some authors include an extra condition that R is set-like, i.e., that the elements less than any given element form a set.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] Equivalently, assuming the axiom of dependent choice, a relation is well-founded when it contains no infinite descending chains, meaning there is no infinite sequence *x*0, *x*1, *x*2, ... of elements of X such that *x**n*+1 *R* *x**n* for every natural number n.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] In order theory, a partial order is called well-founded if the corresponding strict order is a well-founded relation.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] If the order is a total order, then it is called a well-order.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] In set theory, a set x is called a **well-founded set** if the set membership relation is well-founded on the transitive closure of x.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] The axiom of regularity, which is one of the axioms of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory, asserts that all sets are well-founded.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] A relation R is **converse well-founded**, **upwards well-founded**, or **Noetherian** on X, if the converse relation *R*−1 is well-founded on X.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] In this case R is also said to satisfy the ascending chain condition.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] In the context of rewriting systems, a Noetherian relation is also called **terminating**.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] Well-founded induction is sometimes called Noetherian induction, after Emmy Noether.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] On par with induction, well-founded relations also support construction of objects by transfinite recursion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] Let (*X*, *R*) be a set-like well-founded relation and F a function that assigns an object *F*(*x*, *g*) to each pair of an element *x* ∈ *X* and a function g on the set {*y*: *y* *R* *x*} of predecessors of x.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] That is, if we want to construct a function G on X, we may define *G*(*x*) using the values of *G*(*y*) for *y* *R* *x*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] As an example, consider the well-founded relation (**N**, *S*), where **N** is the set of all natural numbers, and S is the graph of the successor function *x* ↦ *x*+1.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] Then induction on S is the usual mathematical induction, and recursion on S gives primitive recursion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] If we consider the order relation (**N**, <), we obtain complete induction, and course-of-values recursion.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] The statement that (**N**, <) is well-founded is also known as the well-ordering principle.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] There are other interesting special cases of well-founded induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] When the well-founded relation is the usual ordering on the class of all ordinal numbers, the technique is called transfinite induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] When the well-founded set is a set of recursively defined data structures, the technique is called structural induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] When the well-founded relation is set membership on the universal class, the technique is known as ∈-induction.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] If (*X*, <) is a well-founded relation and x is an element of X, then the descending chains starting at x are all finite, but this does not mean that their lengths are necessarily bounded.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] Consider the following example: Let X be the union of the positive integers with a new element ω that is bigger than any integer.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] Then X is a well-founded set, but there are descending chains starting at ω of arbitrary great (finite) length; the chain ω, *n* − 1, *n* − 2, ..., 2, 1 has length n for any n.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] The Mostowski collapse lemma implies that set membership is a universal among the extensional well-founded relations: for any set-like well-founded relation R on a class X that is extensional, there exists a class C such that (*X*, *R*) is isomorphic to (*C*, ∈).
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] A relation R is said to be reflexive if *a* *R* *a* holds for every a in the domain of the relation.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] Every reflexive relation on a nonempty domain has infinite descending chains, because any constant sequence is a descending chain.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] For example, in the natural numbers with their usual order ≤, we have 1 ≥ 1 ≥ 1 ≥ ....
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] To avoid these trivial descending sequences, when working with a partial order ≤, it is common to apply the definition of well foundedness (perhaps implicitly) to the alternate relation < defined such that *a* < *b* if and only if *a* ≤ *b* and *a* ≠ *b*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] More generally, when working with a preorder ≤, it is common to use the relation < defined such that *a* < *b* if and only if *a* ≤ *b* and *b* ≰ *a*.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] In the context of the natural numbers, this means that the relation <, which is well-founded, is used instead of the relation ≤, which is not.
[src:structural-induction-pl/well-founded-relation] In some texts, the definition of a well-founded relation is changed from the definition above to include these conventions.
